    <section>
      <title>Section 5.4:
        Eigenvectors and Eigenspaces (GT4) </title>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 5.4.1 (~10 min)</title>
        <p original-id="GT4-s3a2s1p1" internal-id="p-GT4-c-b-a-a">
It's possible to show that <m original-id="GT4-s3a2s1p1m1" internal-id="m-GT4-c-b-a-a-a">-2</m> is an eigenvalue for
<m original-id="GT4-s3a2s1p1m2" internal-id="m-GT4-c-b-a-a-b">\left[\begin{array}{ccc}-1&amp;4&amp;-2\\2&amp;-7&amp;9\\3&amp;0&amp;4\end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p original-id="GT4-s3a2s1p2" internal-id="p-GT4-c-b-a-b">
Compute the kernel of the transformation with standard matrix
<me original-id="GT4-s3a2s1p2m1" internal-id="me-GT4-c-b-a-b-a">
  A-(-2)I
    =
  \left[\begin{array}{ccc} \unknown &amp; 4&amp;-2 \\ 2 &amp; \unknown &amp; 9\\3&amp;0&amp;\unknown \end{array}\right]
</me> 
to find all the eigenvectors <m original-id="GT4-s3a2s1p2m2" internal-id="m-GT4-c-b-a-b-b">\vec x</m> such that <m original-id="GT4-s3a2s1p2m3" internal-id="m-GT4-c-b-a-b-c">A\vec x=-2\vec x</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Definition 5.4.1 </title>
        <p original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1" internal-id="p-GT4-c-d-a-a">
  Since the kernel of a linear map is a subspace
  of <m original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1m1" internal-id="m-GT4-c-d-a-a-a">\IR^n</m>, and the kernel obtained from <m original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1m2" internal-id="m-GT4-c-d-a-a-b">A-\lambda I</m>
  contains all the eigenvectors associated with <m original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1m3" internal-id="m-GT4-c-d-a-a-c">\lambda</m>,
  we call this kernel the <term original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1t4" internal-id="term-GT4-c-d-a-a-d">eigenspace</term><idx original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1i5" internal-id="idx-GT4-c-d-a-a-e">eigenspace</idx> of <m original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1m6" internal-id="m-GT4-c-d-a-a-f">A</m> associated with <m original-id="GT4-s3d4s1p1m7" internal-id="m-GT4-c-d-a-a-g">\lambda</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 5.4.2 (~10 min)</title>
        <p original-id="GT4-s3a5s1p1" internal-id="p-GT4-c-e-a-a">
Find a basis for the eigenspace for the matrix
<m original-id="GT4-s3a5s1p1m1" internal-id="m-GT4-c-e-a-a-a">
  \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
    0 &amp; 0 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 3
  \end{array}\right]
</m>
associated with the eigenvalue <m original-id="GT4-s3a5s1p1m2" internal-id="m-GT4-c-e-a-a-b">3</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 5.4.3 (~10 min)</title>
        <p original-id="GT4-s3a7s1p1" internal-id="p-GT4-c-g-a-a">
Find a basis for the eigenspace for the matrix
<m original-id="GT4-s3a7s1p1m1" internal-id="m-GT4-c-g-a-a-a">
  \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
    5 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 &amp; 4 \\ 6 &amp; -2 &amp; 1 &amp; 5 \\ -2 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; -3 \\ 4 &amp; 5 &amp; -3 &amp; 6
  \end{array}\right]
</m>
associated with the eigenvalue <m original-id="GT4-s3a7s1p1m2" internal-id="m-GT4-c-g-a-a-b">1</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 5.4.4 (~10 min)</title>
        <p original-id="GT4-s3a9s1p1" internal-id="p-GT4-c-i-a-a">
Find a basis for the eigenspace for the matrix
<m original-id="GT4-s3a9s1p1m1" internal-id="m-GT4-c-i-a-a-a">
  \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
    4 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 3 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 5 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 2
  \end{array}\right]
</m>
associated with the eigenvalue <m original-id="GT4-s3a9s1p1m2" internal-id="m-GT4-c-i-a-a-b">2</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>
